After carefully reviewing each entry, we note that none of the “Initial” entries (the starting balances for cash, bank and fixed assets) create any current liability and that most operating “Expense” or “Sale” items do not on their own register a liability on the balance‐sheet. (Sales “Unpaid” are recorded as receivables, not payables.) (Also note that “Interest Receivables” are amounts the business expects to collect so they are assets rather than liabilities.) In our list the only transaction that creates an obligation (a “Purchase” that remains “Unpaid” and is processed via “Account Payable”) is the following entry:

  • Row with id Purchase20231231005 (dated 2023‑12‑31) for Chemical Product D with an amount of 2700000.0; its status is “Unpaid” and its payment method is “Account Payable.”

There is no counter‐transaction (payment) that reduces that obligation in the period. Therefore, while the “initial” balance for current liabilities is zero, at period‑end the only current liability is the 2700000.0 from the one outstanding purchase.

Thus, the final answer is:
